  <discussion>Boerhavia coccinea is weedy and probably adventive along the Gulf and southern
        Atlantic coasts in North America; it can be expected in waste areas anywhere in that region.
        Worldwide, it probably also has a broader range than indicated, particularly on oceanic
        islands. The complex, which is in need of taxonomic clarification, is extremely variable
        with regard to robustness, pubescence, and fruit number in individual terminal
        inflorescences. In the New World, flowers are usually some shade of deep wine red, although
        populations of white-flowered or yellow-flowered plants are rarely found (R. Spellenberg
        2000). In the Old World, pink-flowered plants are frequent (C. Whitehouse
        1996).</discussion>
